Jorge Semprun, the book aims to make these voices heard. In doing so, it clarifies the problems that anyone receiving testimony may encounter and emphasizes the degree to which listening to survivors depends on listening to ourselves and to one another.Witnessing Witnessing seeks to show how, in the situation of address in which Holocaust survivors call upon us, we discover our own tacit assumptions about the nature of community and the very manner in which we practice it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aHolocaust survivorsxPsychology. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xPsychological aspects. 0aPsychic trauma. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Religious.2bisacsh  aart after auschwitz.  ahistory.  aholocaust.  alistening.  amemory.  areception.  asurvivor.  atestimony.  atrauma.  awitnessing.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311072903040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823264056zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823264056423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823264056/original  a978-3-11-072903-0  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK